bably for a like-sounding or like-meaning name in some other European language; see for example   Kaufman  .","History: This name was brought independently to North America from England by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. John Chapmen (sic) was one of the free planters who assented to the ‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatman","meanings":["English: altered form of   Chapman  ."]},{"name":"Kaufman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Chaim, Emanuel, Moshe, Eytan, Herschel, Zvi, Ari, Aron.","Americanized form of German   Kaufmann  , and a variant of the same Jewish surname.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Kaufman</i> meaning ‘merchant’. Compare   Koyfman   2."]},{"name":"Chipman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>chipman</i> (Old English <i>cȳp(e)mann</i>), a side form of <i>chapman</i>, <i>chepman</i> ‘merchant, trader’; see   Chapman  , with which this name was interchangeable."]},{"name":"Copeman","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): patronymic from the early Middle English personal name <i>Cop(e)man</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Scandinavian <i>Kaupmaðr</i>. It is a transferred use of Old Scandinavian <i>kaupmaðr</i> (Old Danish <i>køpman</i>) ‘merchant’, cognate with Old English <i>cēapmann</i> (see   Chapman  ), but there is no evidence for the occupational term in Middle English.","Americanized form of North German   Koopmann   or Dutch   Koopman  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Chapman was born in 1520, in Folkestone, Kent, England, his father, Henry Chapman, was -20 and his mother, Elizabeth Bestney Barker, was 20. He had at least 4 sons with Bennetta Pettit. He died in 1567, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1520–1567":"1520–1567","1524–1578":"1524–1578","1535–1576":"1535–1576","1540–1591":"1540–1591","1542–1628":"1542–1628","–1596":"–1596","1540–1620":"1540–1620","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1591":"1591","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1567":"1567","1578":"1578","1500":"1500","1620":"1620","1576":"1576","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1596":"1596","1540":"1540","1628":"1628","1549":"1549","Folkestone, Kent, England":"Folkestone, Kent, England","England":"England","Folkstone, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1520–1567":"1520–1567","1524–1578":"1524–1578","1535–1576":"1535–1576","1540–1591":"1540–1591","1542–1628":"1542–1628","–1596":"–1596","1540–1620":"1540–1620"